<paragraph id="8BB7368AD843FFCC3CB4FC77330EFF7B" blockId="22.[151,1058,973,1053]" pageId="22" pageNumber="981">
D i a g n o s i s: The extraordinarily rough sculpturing on the surface of this beetle will distinguish it from congeners. The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D09D843FFCC3E59FC5030D0F899" box="[634,751,1002,1023]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Madoniella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="981" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D843FFCC3E59FC5030D0F899" box="[634,751,1002,1023]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="981">Madoniella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
PIC was revised during 2011 (
<bibRefCitation id="EF994B7BD843FFCC3CBCFBBD331AFF7B" author="OPITZ W" box="[159,293,1031,1053]" pageId="22" pageNumber="981" pagination="133 - 248" refId="ref53228" refString="OPITZ W. (2011 b): Classification, natural history, and evolution of the Epiphloeinae (Coleoptera: Cleridae). Part X. The genus Madoniella PIC. - Entomologica Basiliensia et Collectionis Frey 33: 133 - 248." type="journal article" year="2011">OPITZ 2011b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB7368AD843FFCC3CB4FB9631BFFEAF" blockId="22.[151,1059,1067,1481]" pageId="22" pageNumber="981">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 6.0 mm; width 
<quantity id="4CF09B6FD843FFCC3E82FB9130CEFF27" box="[673,753,1067,1089]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="22" pageNumber="981" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
. Form: As in 
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD843FFCC3F5CFB9131EBFF27" box="[895,980,1067,1089]" captionStart="Figs 294-297" captionStartId="101.[151,191,1525,1547]" captionTargetBox="[153,1062,200,1513]" captionTargetId="figure@101.[153,1062,200,1514]" captionTargetPageId="101" captionText="Figs 294-297: Habitus; (294) Madoniella aspera; (295) M. baja; (296) M. delta; (297) M. muralla." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746808" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746808/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="981">Fig. 294</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium castaneous, with wisps of yellow and black setae; antenna bicolored, fundus testaceous, capitulum brown; pronotum castaneous, with wisps of yellow and black setae; pterothorax black; elytra tricolored, side margin mostly castaneous, middle of disc with two large yellow markings bordered by dark castaneous areas, elytral insignia not defined; legs bicolored, base of femora castaneous, remainder testaceous, tibiae mostly testaceous, infuscated at middle; abdomen brown. Head: Cranium coarsely punctate, profusely vested with setae; antenna (
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD843FFCC3E3EFB553057FE63" box="[541,616,1263,1285]" captionStart="Figs 61-91" captionStartId="73.[151,191,1343,1365]" captionTargetBox="[151,1033,198,1310]" captionTargetId="figure@73.[151,1059,198,1328]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="Figs 61-91: Antennae; (61) Madoniella muralla; (62) M. nota; (63) M. acicula; (64) M. aspera; (65) M. baja; (66) M. delta; (67) Amboakis bermejo; (68) Pujoliclerus variolus; (69) Megatrachys irrasis; (70) Cregya arima; (71) Nelsopelonium aspikelum; (72) Cregya vicosa; (73) Pujoliclerus abditus; (74) P. dexus; (75) Cregya triguttula; (76) Pyticeroides brevitubulus; (77) Pujoliclerus lasiosus; (78) Cregya biguttula; (79) Sirpa acara; (80) Parapelonides naranjo; (81) Cregya livida; (82) Amboakis collucoatis; (83) Ampleris jatai; (84) Megaphloeus yasuni; (85) Pelonium implacide, male; (86) Epiphloeus prolixicornus; (87) Pelonium implacide, female; (88) Epiphloeus mantillerii; (89) Amboakis mitaraka; (90) Ellipotoma makrosa; (91) Cregya maura." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746752" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746752/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="981">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antennomeres filiform, progressively shorter towards capitulum, capitular antennomeres 8 and 9 triangular, antennomere 10 ovoid; eyes large, ommatidia small, eye notch large, eye narrower than frons (EW/FW 20/40). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD843FFCC3E5EFAF930E2FE3C" box="[637,733,1347,1370]" captionStart="Figs 118-133" captionStartId="76.[151,191,1373,1395]" captionTargetBox="[152,1050,202,1340]" captionTargetId="figure@76.[152,1056,202,1357]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="Figs 118-133: Pronota; (118) Pujoliclerus abditus; (119) Nelsopelonium aspikelum; (120) Parapelonides naranjo; (121) Pujoliclerus lasiosus; (122) Neorthopleura rubra; (123) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (124) Ichnea cerinis; (125) Ampleris amazon; (126) Pujoliclerus abditus; (127) P. dexsus; (128) Sirpa acara; (129) Madoniella aspera; (130) Pelonium tayrona; (131) Megatrachys irrasis; (132) Ordinis taxis; (133) Pujoliclerus cnecostus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746758" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746758/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="981">Fig. 129</figureCitation>
) slightly transverse, coarsely punctured (PW/PL 80/70), disc coarsely sculptured, densely setose, deeply concave paralaterally near pronotal collar; discal and lateral trichobothria prominent; elytral surface very rough, highly setose, asetiferous punctures large, not striate (EL/EW 120/60); anterior margin of protibia with 3 spines. Abdomen: Pygidium scutiform.
</paragraph>
